    "body": "<!--\r\n**PLEASE READ THIS FIRST:**\r\n- DO NOT use the bug and feature tracker for general questions and support requests.\r\n  Use the `cython-users` mailing list instead.\r\n  It has a wider audience, so you get more and better answers.\r\n- Did you search for similar issues already?\r\n  Please do, it helps to save us precious time that we otherwise could not invest into development.\r\n- Did you try the latest master branch or pre-release?\r\n  It might already have what you want to report.\r\n  Also see the [Changelog](https://github.com/cython/cython/blob/master/CHANGES.rst) regarding recent changes.\r\n-->\r\n\r\n**Describe the bug**\r\n`cpdef` function calling `cdef` function that raises in case of a return value of -1 would silently ignore the exception and simply skip executing the chunk of code starting from the `cdef` function.\r\n\r\nThis IMO is a *very* bad behavior/feature/bug, b/c it makes debugging very hard and confusing.\r\n\r\n**To Reproduce**\r\nCode to reproduce the behaviour:\r\n```\r\ncdef class Dummy:\r\n\r\n    cdef int test(self) nogil except -1:\r\n        return -1   # should raise\r\n\r\n\r\ncpdef void test() except *:\r\n    cdef Dummy d = Dummy()\r\n\r\n    print(\"before d.test\")\r\n    d.test()\r\n    print(\"called d.test\")\r\n```\r\n\r\n**Expected behavior**\r\nI would expect `d.test()` to raise and that exception gets propagated to the caller `test` as well.\r\n\r\nInstead, if you run the above, anything after line `d.test()` (inclusive) is simply ignored w/o any error/warning msgs!\r\n\r\n**Environment (please complete the following information):**\r\n - OS: Linux (Centos)\r\n - Python version 3.8\r\n - Cython version 3.0a10\r\n\r\n**Additional context**\r\nAdd any other context about the problem here.\r\n",
