            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "> No. You're misunderstanding how it works.\r\n> \r\n> ```\r\n> cdef int test(self) nogil except -1:\r\n>     return -1   # should raise\r\n> ```\r\n> \r\n> What this says is: if Cython raises an error, then it'll use a value of -1 to indicate it to the caller. It does not say that a value of -1 is converted into an exception. All `return -1` will do is confuse the caller (because it expects an exception to be set).\r\n> \r\n> What you want is something like:\r\n> \r\n> ```\r\n> cdef int test(self) nogil except -1:\r\n>     raise ValueError\r\n> ```\r\n\r\nSo `except -1` is just a way for caller to realize that it needs to propagate the exception raised inside the `cdef` function. \r\n\r\nIf there's no exception detected, it behaves like a normal `cdef` function (i.e. just returns -1 and that's it)? \r\n\r\nBut then why `print(\"called d.test\")` part of the example above was skipped since there's no exception raised.",
