        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "> except ?-1\r\n\r\nI see... so let me summarize to make sure:\r\n\r\nFirst of all, picking `except -1` over `except *` (c only. no c++) is largely due the function return type (i.e. `int`) here, so faster (i.e. only check one value), and it's *only a signal* to the caller for checking and propagating exception(s). \r\n\r\nIf, for example, we wanna to *raise* if an index is -1, re-using the example above, we should just `raise` inside the `cdef` function to be safe, instead of `return -1` and counting on the caller to *treat* it as an exception (which it won't).  \r\n\r\nFinally, the reason why I saw the weird behavior (to me) above that the function runs but everything after `d.test()` is ignored, is b/c I was basically doing something **undefined**, i.e. telling the caller that there's an exception, but there's not, which is undefined.\r\n",
